post_text:
The Tea Area School District is again participating in Feeding South Dakota's Backpack Program. The backpack program provides children with a bag of food to help fight hunger over weekends and long holidays from school. We are looking for volunteers to pick up packages from Feeding SD and deliver them to Frontier Elementary each week. The bags are then distributed to each of the schools and sent home with students enrolled in the program. Each week there will be 5 to 6 totes that need to be picked up from Feeding South Dakota.

Please use this link if you are able to help: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/30e0a45acae23aaff2-20202021

We greatly appreciate all those that help us provide this important service for families in our community! Thank you!

post_text: Here is a tip from our Titan Care Team as we prepare for school this next week! 7. Keep explanations age-appropriate. For early elementary school children, provide brief, simple information. Give simple examples of the steps people make every day to stop germs and stay healthy, such as washing hands. Use language such as “adults are working hard to keep you safe.” For upper elementary and middle school children, they may need assistance separating reality from rumor and fantasy. Discuss the efforts national, state, and community leaders are doing to prevent germs from spreading. For high school students, issues can be discussed in more depth. Provide honest, accurate, and factual information about the current status of COVID-19. Be a good listener!

post_text:
A tip from our Titan Care Team:

Start the back-to-school routine of an earlier bedtime and a set wake-up time to help your child’s body prepare for school at least one to two weeks ahead of time. You may need to cover windows with a sheet and start the wind-down routine earlier, with a snack, book, and quiet music. This new regular schedule provides everyone a sense of control, predictability, calm, and well-being.

post_text:
Titan Families,

We are in the process of updating our information messaging system. The purpose is to create a uniform delivery mode for parents, students, and patrons across the District. The new service is through Remind. The service will allow an app notification, text message, and eventually two-way calling. It has come to our attention this morning that the sync did not go well on Friday. We thought the sync did not work on Friday. Based on feedback, it sent out a message but incorrectly sync to emergency contacts and former accounts.

We apologize for the confusion and are working on the platform.

If you have not registered on our online system, please do so as soon as possible. It works best to register on a computer.

As an additional note, activity passes are not currently available as the Board will identify event capacity levels this evening. All Tea Area events held at the football field and/or high school gym will be live-streamed at no cost to Titan fans.

Have a great week!
Jenn

Dr. Jennifer N Lowery
Tea Area Superintendent of Schools

June 17 at 1:52 PM ·

We understand that operating your business during the COVID-19 pandemic has been a challenge. We want to support you by promoting your business through our #ChooseTea Social Media Campaign.

To participate in this campaign please submit a short video 15 - 30 seconds max that tells us a little about your business and answers the following questions:

1. Why is it important to buy local?

2. How does buying local impact Tea?

The video can be submitted directly to email at teachamberfordevelopment@gmail.com

We are asking that the videos be submitted by Friday, June 30 – if possible.

Each week, the Tea Chamber for Development will post a business video on the Tea Chamber for Development Facebook Page with the #ChooseTea and boost the post so your business reaches a wider audience

5.15.20

Titans,
It is hard to believe this year is coming to a close. I am still not sure what day, month, or time of year it feels like, but today was the last day of school. We are glad you are Titans. We are already busy planning for the next school year.

Please remember your exchange time on Monday, Tuesday, or Wednesday.
I believe signup genius will send you a reminder the day before your signup
time. Please do not hesitate to call the buildings beginning on Monday if you
have any questions. We are here to support you and your student.

Thank you for a wonderful and memorable school year. This year will be remembered in history for a long time to come.

If you are looking for an email or message, most information can be found within our Parent Resource Guide https://docs.google.com/document/d/1PieSzucwjPP_LK3ynt9ARI1IWAut0_7GIT5UwYLLc_4/edit?usp=sharing.

Blessings to you and your family for a safe, healthy, and memorable summer,
Jenn
Dr. Jennifer Nebelsick Lowery
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
5.6.2020

Titan Families,

Happy Teacher Appreciation Week! We appreciate our Titan Teachers and that includes each of you. Parents, grandparents, friends, brothers, sisters, and neighbors are all teachers. We appreciate how Titans have all come together to take care of one another and especially our students. We appreciate the planning, leadership, and care of our faculty. We are successful only because we are together providing a high-quality solution for our Titan student. Thank you to being part of our Titan Team.

Titan Care Team Tip of the Day:
Do meaningful things with your free time. Learn a new skill, create art, journal, play puzzles or games, or cook something new. Think about something you have wanted to learn or do for a long time. Having a goal or task to work on can help you relax.

Have a wonderful evening,
Jenn
Dr. Jennifer Nebelsick Lowery
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
5.5.2020

Titan Families,

My update is short on this beautiful evening. I hope each of you are all doing well.

Please find our Titan Care Team:
Practice relaxing in the present moment through mindfulness. Mindfulness involves focusing your attention on the present moment and accepting it without judgment. There are many types of mindfulness exercises, but each typically involves finding a quiet, comfortable place where you can observe your thoughts and focus on your breath. Some apps to explore include Headspace, Calm, Simple Habit, and Liberate. This Mayo Clinic mindfulness program https://newsnetwork.mayoclinic.org/discussion/covid-19-tips-for-mindfulness-coping-with-anxiety/ is a great place to start.

Week of May 11 Meal Sign up https://forms.gle/krS1cPsoBHECZiNZ7
Please sign up for breakfast and lunches for the week of May 11 by Tuesday, May 5th, 7pm.

Have a wonderful evening,
Jenn
Dr. Jennifer Nebelsick Lowery
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Update 4.15.2020

Titan Families,

I spend most of my days on multiple conference calls or phone calls from my office desk with other adults talking, planning, and brainstorming. Today, I had the opportunity to join Mr. Knudson, Mr. Preheim, and the senior class officers as they collaboratively reviewed senior class feedback. Our students are incredible, respectful, and care deeply. Two of the three students were 4th-graders when I was principal at the Intermediate School. It is amazing to see them grow and become young adults. Education is the greatest profession in the world because we get to watch, nurture, push, and grow our next leaders. Today, the call rejuvenated me as our halls are empty but they refilled my energy and spirit.

By the end of the week, we hope to release a comprehensive plan identifying how report cards, transcripts, graduation, and item pick-up/drop-off will work. We sincerely appreciate your patience.

Resources:
District Parent Resource Guide https://drive.google.com/open?id=1PieSzucwjPP_LK3ynt9ARI1IWAut0_7GIT5UwYLLc_4

We love being able to deliver Hood's out in the communities! Visiting with schools, daycares, and other businesses and getting to show them what we've been working on has always been a highlight for us. There's no way around it, we miss you guys!

But guess what?! We are still going to be giving you everything you've come to love about Hood PLUS MORE!

You can access our brand new interactive digital edition just by clicking the link below. Put those pj's on, find the comfy spot on the couch, and enjoy a magazine like you've never seen before!

Need advice how to get through this time? We got it! Looking for some Easter crafts and snacks? We got it! Want to meet an inspiring teen? We got it! Want to hear sweet messages from some amazing educators to their students that were nominated for Educator of the Year? Yep, we got those too! Not to mention, our first ever preschool directory!

Catch up with us now and enjoy our new April issue! Click below! 👇

post_text:
Update 4.1.2020

Titan Families,

Happy April Fools Day! It is a good thing that COVID19 crisis did not start today or no one would believe it was real. Sadly, it is quite real and now is the time to take care of one another in unique ways. Facetime, google meet, old fashion letters are wonderful ways to take care of one another!

As a reminder, our playgrounds are locked and equipment is closed. Please support the city and the district’s efforts to keep people safe from this invisible enemy. Please do your part to be part of the solution. We care about each and everyone of you!

Today is Census Day! It is very important to take part in the 2020 census. As a member of the chamber board, I know businesses consider towns when they officially reach 5000 people. Tea would benefit if we were officially identified as a community over 5000. I believe you can do it right here: https://my2020census.gov/

Remember the District Parent Resource Guide is the centralized location for information and resources.

Sincerely,
Jennifer
Dr. Jennifer Nebelsick Lowery
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Titans,

The purpose of this email is to provide an overview of Tea Area School District's COVID19 response and centralize our parent resources.

The attached resource is a ten-thousand foot overview of our technology, instructional program, and community resources. The attachment is also available by clicking this link. The linked document will be updated as we learn from each other.

As a parent, I strongly encourage you to identify a learning area for each of your children. This area should be consistent, free from distraction, and appropriate for devices. We already lost a power cord at our home, but it was easily found as we have not gone anywhere. Now, I have a storage bin by each of their learning areas to keep their school items together.

Your principals and teachers will be in contact with you on Sunday and Monday with specific information. I am grateful for their work and organization.

Thank you all for your support and grace,
Jenn

post_text: While I was at work, my three kids rocked their “school schedule”. They rotated every 30 minutes with activities to complete. Here is a list of their favorites: Using a tape measure to measure 10 things in the house, record the measure, and then visit the objects in order from smallest to largest; slap jack; creating a zoo out of legos, treasure hunt (definitely a repeat activity), Yahtzee, lining up the four-year-old’s stuff animals and reading stories to her, and Ticket to Ride. Tomorrow they are going to write a play, record it, and send it to their grandparents (if they do not end up in an argument). They are also suppose to create an obstacle course in the basement with five stations.

Tea Area Curriculum & Assessment
February 19 at 1:15 PM ·

Dear Tea Area Families,

Registration for 2020-2021 Kindergarten is NOW OPEN! Kindergarten registration is ONLINE ONLY and is for all children living in the Tea Area School district who will be 5 years old on or before September 1st, 2020.

Online Registration will be February 18 - March 20. Current families, please use the link on our Tea Area Homepage to register. Once registration is complete, a link will be sent to your email address allowing you to choose your time for kindergarten screening on Friday, March 27th.

Note: If your child is currently in junior kindergarten at Tea
Area for the 19-20 school year, you do NOT need to register them for kindergarten or complete the screening process.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to contact Amanda Treloar, Tea Area Registrar at 498-2700 Option 4.

#TitanPride

The 2020 Tea Sports Rumble Basketball Tournament hosted by the Tea Area Sports Boosters is fast approaching (..this weekend!) and we are still in need of volunteers for gate & concession workers as well as food donations. These basketball tournaments are our largest fundraisers of the year and in order to be successful, we need your assistance. This year, we are asking for volunteers to not only help us with covering gate, concessions and court monitoring, we are also asking for donations of food items for our concessions.

Won’t you please considered making a gift of your time and/or resources to this worthy fundraiser?

The following SignUp Genius link will show all of the concession items we are asking to be donated for our tournament:

https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20F044AACAD2AA0FC1-20206

The following link will allow you to sign up for any of the shifts that are required:

https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20F044AACAD2AA0FC1-20207

Regards,

Tea Area Sports Boosters

Studer Education
January 30 at 3:54 PM ·

Join us for the Symposium on Continuous Improvement with the School District of Menomonee Falls this spring.

Building and sustaining a system of quality is often where organizations struggle the most.

During this two-day symposium, your team will learn about the School District of Menomonee Falls' journey to continuous improvement and the partners who have been critical in developing a high-performing system with a supportive work culture. Teams leave this event beginning a deeper conversation about how to build a culture committed to learning and focused on quality outcomes for the community.

Participants will have opportunities to visit classrooms and speak to staff about tactics and strategies that create continuous improvement throughout the school district. From kindergarten students all the way to the board, process improvement has an impact on system effectiveness and efficiency.
